        ukrainian_flag_day_description: '🇺🇦 Ukrainian State Flag Day is a national holiday of Ukraine, celebrated annually on August 23. This day is dedicated to the symbol of Ukraine\'s independence and sovereignty — the blue and yellow flag.\n\nThe blue color symbolizes the cloudless sky, and the yellow represents the golden wheat fields, which are traditional symbols of Ukraine. The flag is a symbol of national unity, freedom and independence.\n\nOn this day, Ukrainians around the world honor the national flag and celebrate the importance of preserving Ukrainian identity and culture.',
        ukrainian_independence_day: 'August 24 — Ukrainian Independence Day',
        ukrainian_independence_day_description: '📌 Background\n\nIn August 1991, the GKChP (coup attempt) occurred in Moscow, when part of the USSR leadership tried to restore strict control.\n\nThe coup attempt failed, and in the USSR republics, sentiments for independence sharply intensified.\n\nIn Kyiv on August 22, blue-yellow flags were already being raised en masse — first on buildings, then above the Verkhovna Rada.\n\n📌 August 24, 1991\n\nThe Verkhovna Rada of the Ukrainian SSR convened an emergency session.\n\nDeputies discussed the situation and the threat of dictatorship returning from Moscow.\n\nThere was a tense but solemn atmosphere in the hall: they understood that the fate of the country was being decided.\n\nAs a result:\n\n346 out of 450 deputies voted "for" (this is an overwhelming majority).\n\nThe Act of Declaration of Independence of Ukraine was adopted.\n\n📌 What this document meant\n\nUkraine declared itself an independent democratic state.\n\nThe supremacy of Ukrainian laws throughout the territory was affirmed.\n\nIt was established that all state bodies are subordinate only to the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine.\n\n📌 Why exactly August 24\n\nThis was a consequence of the GKChP failure (August 19-21).\n\nPopular pressure was enormous: thousands of people came out under the parliament.\n\nThe deputies understood that missing the moment meant remaining in the USSR, where everything could return to square one.\n\n📌 After this\n\nAugust 24 was proclaimed Ukrainian Independence Day.\n\nAnd to consolidate the decision, a referendum was scheduled for December 1, 1991, where the people had to confirm or refute this act.\n\nIn the referendum, 90.32% of citizens voted "for" independence.\n\n⚡ Thus, it was on August 24, 1991, that Ukraine legally declared its independence, and on December 1, the people confirmed it.',
