        eurovision_title: '🎶 Vienna is preparing for a grand celebration of the 70th anniversary of Eurovision',
        eurovision_text: 'The Austrian capital will become the main center of the song show in 2026. Rathausplatz will once again become Eurovillage, where fans can watch the semi-finals and final of the competition for free on large screens, and the Euroclub will be opened directly within the walls of Vienna City Hall this time. The main concerts will take place at Wiener Stadthalle — a 16,000-seat arena that has already hosted Eurovision in 2015.\n\nThe city mayor confirmed that Vienna will allocate 22.6 million euros for the organization, despite the current austerity program. For comparison: Liverpool spent 16 million €, Malmö — 18 million €, Turin — 30 million €, and Basel planned 33.5 million €. The return of the competition to Vienna is explained not only by the symbolism of the anniversary show, but also by the convenience of the city — modern airports, railway connections and a large selection of hotels make it an ideal place for fans from all over Europe.',
        austria_facts_title: '🇦🇹 5 facts about Austria that will surprise you (Part 2)',
        austria_facts_text: '1. **Austria has its own "sea" landscape**\n\nDespite the country having no access to the sea, there are incredible lakes here — for example, Wolfgangsee and Wörthersee, where the water is so clear that the bottom is visible for several meters.\n\n2. **The oldest zoo in the world**\n\nSchönbrunn Zoo in Vienna has been operating since 1752 and is the oldest continuously operating zoo on the planet. Rare pandas and other exotic animals live here.\n\n3. **Lifts without doors? It\'s a reality!**\n\nIn some old Viennese buildings, "paternoster" type lifts still operate — without doors and with continuous cabin movement. A unique find for the brave!\n\n4. **One of the best chocolates in the world is produced here**\n\nMozartkugel chocolate, originating from Salzburg, has become a gastronomic legend of Austria. It is still made according to traditional recipes for over 100 years.\n\n5. **The largest glacier in the Eastern Alps**\n\nThe Pasterze Glacier near Grossglockner mountain is a natural wonder visited by thousands of tourists every year. Its length is over 8 km!',
        molotov_ribbentrop_title: '📜 August 23, 1939 — Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact',
        molotov_ribbentrop_text: '86 years ago, on August 23, 1939, the Non-Aggression Pact between Germany and the USSR, the so-called "Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact", and secret protocols to it were signed in Moscow, according to which Hitler and Stalin agreed to divide Europe.\n\nThis event became the trigger for World War II, which began with a joint attack on Poland by two totalitarian regimes - the Nazi Third Reich from the west and the communist USSR from the east. These military operations were the embodiment of the secret protocols signed in Moscow and ended with a joint military parade of Wehrmacht and Red Army units in Brest on the territory of occupied Poland.',
        molotov_ribbentrop_text_short: '86 years ago, on August 23, 1939, the Non-Aggression Pact between Germany and the USSR, the so-called "Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact", and secret protocols to it were signed in Moscow, according to which Hitler and Stalin agreed to divide Europe.\n\nThis event became the trigger for World War II, which began with a joint attack on Poland by two totalitarian regimes - the Nazi Third Reich from the west and the communist USSR from the east. These military operations were the embodiment of the secret protocols signed in Moscow and ended with a joint military parade of Wehrmacht and Red Army units in Brest on the territory of occupied Poland.',
        molotov_ribbentrop_text_full: '86 years ago, on August 23, 1939, the Non-Aggression Pact between Germany and the USSR, the so-called "Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact", and secret protocols to it were signed in Moscow, according to which Hitler and Stalin agreed to divide Europe.\n\nThis event became the trigger for World War II, which began with a joint attack on Poland by two totalitarian regimes - the Nazi Third Reich from the west and the communist USSR from the east. These military operations were the embodiment of the secret protocols signed in Moscow and ended with a joint military parade of Wehrmacht and Red Army units in Brest on the territory of occupied Poland.\n\nToday, the lessons of the past are more relevant than ever. Just as 86 years ago, Moscow\'s main goal is to divide spheres of influence and forcibly redraw borders in Europe. Just as then, any appeasement of such plans or the conclusion of secret agreements with Moscow can only lead to global catastrophe.\n\nThe events of 1938-1939, culminating in the signing of the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact and the beginning of World War II, demonstrated that appeasing an aggressor does not bring peace; it always leads only to greater war. Then, the consequence of short-sighted policy and cowardice was the death of 70 to 85 million people, unprecedented atrocities and destruction, a global catastrophe for humanity.\n\nThe international community has no right to repeat these mistakes today, when the Russian Federation has unleashed the bloodiest war of aggression in Europe since World War II and has brought back to European soil the unprecedented atrocities of that time, which Russian occupiers are committing during aggression against Ukraine.\n\nIt is telling that the modern regime in Moscow is making every effort to manipulate history and distort the historical truth about August 23, 1939. The signing of the non-aggression pact between the Third Reich and the USSR is justified by various opportunistic arguments, and the fact of a joint attack with the Nazis and the dismemberment of Poland is presented as supposedly strategic necessity. All this contradicts historical documents and testimonies.\n\nWe call on the international community to resolutely condemn Russian manipulations and whitewashing of this and other crimes of the Soviet Union and Stalin\'s regime. It is necessary to double joint efforts to study, preserve and promote the historical truth about the causes and consequences of World War II. Correct conclusions from the past will prevent catastrophic mistakes in the present and future.\n\nIn the context of the current situation, we once again express support for efforts to achieve peace through strength thanks to the leadership of the United States and personally US President Donald Trump, the active role of European allies. We emphasize that Ukraine, like no one else, seeks to end the war and restore comprehensive, just and sustainable peace, is ready for the most effective work with partners to achieve this goal. We separately emphasize the importance of providing effective security guarantees from the United States and European allies for Ukraine in the peace process.\n\nIn light of the lessons of the past, we emphasize that to achieve just peace, it is necessary to increase pressure on the aggressor state Russia and strengthen Ukraine\'s defense capability and resilience. A just end to Russian aggression will be the best evidence that the international community has learned from the mistakes of the 20th century, and that the slogan "Never again!" really has practical meaning for modern generations. The right of might should never become higher than the force of international law, and the desire for peace cannot be a justification for appeasing an aggressor. The events of the past must be a lesson we have learned, not a mistake we have repeated. Together we are capable of protecting the world from this.',
